<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-s01e04" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Episode 4: Order of Operations (PEMDAS)</title>
 <assemblage>
  <title>Episode 4 Learning Goals</title>
  <p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          Perform multi-step calculations in order using PEMDAS 
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Recognize “hidden” parentheses / grouping, for example, when division is represented using a horizontal bar 
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </p>
 </assemblage>

 <p>
  In problems where we have to do more than one operation (addition and multiplication, or maybe division and subtraction and exponents),
   we have rules for the order of those operations.
   <ol>
    <li>
      <p>
        <alert>Parentheses</alert>: First, do operations inside parentheses.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        <alert>Exponent</alert>: Then, calculate exponents.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        <alert>Multiplication/Division</alert>: Then, do all the multiplication and division in the problem from <em>left to right</em>.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        <alert>Addition/Subtraction</alert>: Then, do all the addition and subtraction in the problem from <em>left to right</em>.
      </p>
    </li>
   </ol>
 </p>
 <p>
  We remember the order of operations using the mnemonic PEMDAS (“please excuse my dear Aunt Sally”).
 </p>

 <example>
  <p>
    Calculate <m>2^6 + \frac{6}{3} -2(5+3)</m>
  </p>
  <p>
    Solution:
  </p>
  <p>
    <alert>P</alert>: First, we do the calculation in the parentheses, <m>5+3=8</m>.
    <md>
      2^6 + \frac{6}{3} - 2(8)
    </md>
  </p>
  <p>
    <alert>E</alert>: Then, we calculate the exponent, <m>2^6=64</m>.
    <md>
      64 + \frac{6}{3} - 2(8)
    </md>
  </p>
  <p>
    <alert>MD</alert>: Then, we do the division and multiplication, from left to right. As we read the calculation from left to right, 
    we see the division <m>\frac{6}{3}=2</m>, so we calculate that next:
    <md>
      64 + 2 - 2(8)
    </md>
    As we continue to read the calculation from left to right, we see the multiplication <m>2(8)=16</m>, so we calculate that next:
    <md>
      64 + 2 - 16
    </md>
  </p>
  <p>
    <alert>AS</alert>: Then, we do the addition and subtraction, from left to right. 
    As we read the calculation from left to right, we see the addition <m>64+2 = 66</m>, so we calculate that next:
    <md>
      66 - 16
    </md>
    Finally, this subtraction is all that's left:
  <md>
    66-16=50
  </md>
  </p>
 </example>

 <p>
  There are a few things that should be considered the same as parentheses when doing PEMDAS calculations.
  <ol marker="A)">
    <li>
      <p>
        Brackets
      </p>
      <p>
        Sometimes brackets [ ] are used instead of parentheses ( ) in multi-step calculations.
        <md>
          3[7-2]
        </md>
        So calculate the operations inside the brackets first:
        <md>
          3[7-2] = 3[5] = 15
        </md>
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Division
      </p>
      <p>
        When division is represented using the horizontal bar, you should pretend that there are parentheses around what's above the bar and around what's below the bar:
        <md>
          \frac{3+7}{1+1} \hspace{0.5in} \text{should be treated like}\hspace{0.5in} \frac{(3+7)}{(1+1)}
        </md>
        So calculate the addition above and below the fraction bar first:
        <md>
          \frac{10}{2} = 5
        </md>
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Some problems contain nested parentheses / brackets. If this happens, work from the inside out, starting with the calculations in the innermost parentheses.
      </p>
    </li>
  </ol>
 </p>

 <example>
  <p>
    Calculate
    <md>
      4+2[15-3(5-1)]
    </md>
    We start with the calculation <m>5-1</m> in the innermost set of parentheses:
    <md>
      4+2[15-3(4)]
    </md>
    Then, we work on the problem <m>8-3(4)</m> inside the brackets. Using PEMDAS here, we should do the multiplication <m>3(4)</m> before doing the subtraction.
    <md>
      4+2[15-12]
    </md>
    Now we complete the subtraction <m>15-12</m> to finish the calculation inside the brackets:
    <md>
      4+2[3]
    </md>
    Using PEMDAS again, we should do the multiplication before the addition:
    <md>
      4+2[3] = 4+ 6
    </md>
    <md>
      4+ 6 = 10
    </md>
  </p>
 </example>
